{South must pick an opening bid with a balanced-ish 13 and no five-card major. The choice comes down to suit length and the lesson's tie-breakers.
[show S]
[BID 1D]
@S @v(have|has) 13 with a five-card diamond suit and no biddable major, so @v(open|opens) the longest suit and @v(start|starts) the description at the one level.
[show N]
[BID 1S]
With a good six-card spade suit and an opening hand of @your own, @S @v(respond|responds) in the major to look for a fit.
[BID 2S]
@S @v(rebound|rebounds) the long spades, showing the six-card suit and inviting partner to keep going.
[BID 3S]
Still driving toward game, @S @v(repeat|repeats) the suit to confirm length and extra values.
[BID 4S]
With a clear eight-card fit and enough combined strength, @S @v(bid|bids) the spade game.
[show NS]
South opened the longest suit, North showed and rebid the six spades, and the partnership climbed naturally to a sound 4S. Choosing the long suit at the one level kept the auction simple.}
[BidSystemEW "2/1GF - 2/1 Game Force"]
[BidSystemNS "2/1GF - 2/1 Game Force"]

